Title:
SharpCOM

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
SharpCOM is a C# “weaponized” port of Invoke-DCOM, implementing DCOM-based lateral movement for remote command execution on Windows systems. It builds on the SharpSploit DCOM module work and packages it as a standalone executable suitable for in-memory execution (e.g., Cobalt Strike `execute-assembly`). The tool supports multiple DCOM execution methods (example shown: `ShellWindows`) and targets a specified remote computer name to launch an arbitrary command. It’s primarily useful for red teams and pentesters operating in Windows/AD environments where DCOM is available and remote execution is needed without traditional service creation techniques. The project is interesting because it operationalizes a well-known lateral movement primitive into a practical C# implant-friendly utility.

Technical Focus:
- DCOM-based remote code execution (lateral movement)
- COM object instantiation and method invocation over the network
- Windows RPC/DCOM communication paths
- Tradecraft for in-memory .NET execution (e.g., Beacon execute-assembly)
- Porting PowerShell tradecraft to C# tooling

Use Cases:
- Remote command execution on Windows hosts via DCOM
- Lateral movement in AD environments where DCOM is permitted
- Post-exploitation execution through Cobalt Strike Beacon `execute-assembly`
- Testing and validating DCOM-related detections and hardening controls

Keywords:
SharpCOM, Invoke-DCOM, DCOM, COM, lateral movement, remote command execution, Windows RPC, ShellWindows, Cobalt Strike, Beacon, execute-assembly, SharpSploit, .NET, C#, post-exploitation, Windows internals, remote activation, OPSEC, red team tooling